To reduce random variation for an individual and better represent long-term dietary intake, cumulative averages of the aMed score from the repeated FFQs were calculated (averaging together scores from two prior years).  Adjustments were made for “confounders” (factors that could confuse results) by adjusting for age, smoking, BMI, menopausal status, postmenopausal hormone use, multivitamin intake, alcohol intake, physical activity and aspirin use.

Cox proportional-hazard modeling was used to assess the association between an aMed score and risk of CHD and stroke, using separate models for fatal and nonfatal CHD and stroke types. 

Greater adherence to the Mediterranean diet, as reflected by a higher aMed diet score, was associated with a lower risk of incident CHD and stroke in women.  During 20 years of follow-up, 2391 incident cases of CHD, 1763 incident cases of stroke and 1077 cardiovascular disease deaths (fatal CHD and strokes combined) were found. Women in the top aMed quintile were at lower risk for both CHD and stroke compared with those in the bottom quintile (relative risk [RR], 0.71).

Hitler is alive in Burma, the sign says.

Ellen Page, star of Juno, stands alone on a street corner with a piece of cardboard held above her head, the unsettling message scribbled with Sharpie onto her sign. Burma, also known as Myanmar, is a Southeastern Asian country ruled by a tyrannical militant junta who came into power in 1962 through the act of a coup d’état. In 2007 a number of street protests occurred, the first public protests in a decade. Led by a large number of Burmese monks, these protests earned the name “The Saffron Revolution”, christened after the color of the robes that the monks wore. After the first few initial uprisings the public at large began taking an interest in the protests, and while at first the Burmese government begrudgingly allowed the monks to engage in peaceful gatherings, soon the violence escalated into what some considered an all-out war between the monks and the military junta, with the military actively invading and ransacking monasteries around the country. Foreign journalists were rounded up and imprisoned on sight, with a Japanese photojournalist named Kenji Nagai killed on September 27th, 2007, simply for being present at a street protest. While the official death toll rests at 13 killed, Colonel Hla Win, who defected from the army some days prior to the official report, is quoted as having said, “Many more people have been killed in recent days than you’ve heard about. The bodies can be counted in several thousand.”

This is nothing new. While these are some of the most recent examples of atrocities taking place in our world, a government’s desire to quash dissent and maintain complete rule over its citizenry has been around for as long as civilization itself. Early Roman emperors declared themselves chosen by the gods to have complete executive ruling over every aspect of their society. Japanese emperors are believed to actually be gods, sent to our world to lead their people to prosperity through the invention of Motorola cell phones and hara-kiri, and our current president, George W. Bush, has weekly conference calls with Ted Haggard, the leader of Stupid People Worldwide, a subsidiary group of the Republic Party.

Some of the most well known examples of these actions are such incidents as the 1989 June 4th protest at Tiananmen Square, where intellectuals, labor activists, and students all gathered to protest the authoritarian rule of the government. The death toll in that particular instance ranges wildly, with official reports from the Chinese government stating 200-300 dead to reports let out by the Chinese Red Cross, declaring between 2,000-3,000 dead.  Another is the Rwandan genocide of the 1990s, where Hutu militia groups, aided by the Rwandan government, began a systematic killing of all Tutsis, as well as political moderates, irrespective of their ethnic backgrounds. Hitler’s ‘Third Reich’, a period spanning several years and several countries where anyone of Jewish background was rounded up and killed, is another extreme example.

Duke Ellington’s legacy in jazz derives in large part from his longevity and, by extension, his creative abilities to shape his orchestra. Ellington’s presence on the piano is subtle in many of the compositions selected for this assignment, but as a composer Ellington excelled at creating rich and complex pieces that showcased the individual abilities of band members. Ellington crafted the framework in which a soloist could freely improvise, in addition to writing tightly orchestrated pieces and phrases that called on the particular style of band members to highlight musical ideas. In doing this, he also emphasized the tone of the orchestra more generally, creating coherent and original sounds to fit each piece. Ellington’s mastery of the individual players’ sound, as well as how they fit together in a growing ensemble, enabled him to write some of the most innovative and brilliant pieces in jazz history.
The Grove Music dictionary, in discussing Ellington’s sound and innovation, mentions Creole Love Call in reference to using voice “as a jazz instrument” throughout his career.  This is an early example of Ellington’s use of voice to add texture and color without the hindrance of lyrics. Creole Love Call also demonstrates Ellington’s ability to compliment the style of his soloists, something that is evident throughout his career. This slow, deliberate twelve bar blues piece contains six choruses, as follows:
Chorus 1: Call and response between voice and reeds, where the voice begins smooth and melodic, then transitions to a rougher sound towards the end.
Chorus 2: Muted trumpet solo that elaborates on the basic melody and emphasizes several extended blue notes.
Chorus 3: Sweeping clarinet solo in a high register, backed by a subtle syncopated piano phrase.
Chorus 4: Full band echoes the first chorus with a call and response by the brass and reed sections.
Chorus 5: The climactic chorus of the piece, as the reeds now begin the call and response in a high register, backed by syncopated stop time from the brass and rhythm sections.
Chorus 6: A return to the structure of the first chorus, with call and response between voice and reeds. In this chorus the voice takes on the sound of the “growl” technique, soloing as an instrument.
Tag: Brief tag featuring a vocal run and a dissonant novelty ending by a trombone.
Ellington’s use of voice to add a dimension of tone color to this piece is one example of a stylistic trait that permeates his work. 
In Hot and Bothered, recorded a year later, Ellington combines his skill at tight orchestration with his ear for tone color. A call and response phrase between “Bubber” Miley on muted trumpet and Baby Cox’s scat singing uses the vocal elements of Miley’s playing and instrumental aspects of Cox’s voice to create a rich and complementary sound. It Don’t Mean a Thing (If It Ain’t Got That Swing) extends these ideas, as Ellington uses Joe “Tricky Sam” Nanton, a mainstay in Ellington’s orchestra, to great effect in introducing the melody on muted trombone.

Why do organisms evolve in the manner that they do‭? ‬Are there restrictions or constraints that influence the direction of evolutionary change‭? ‬Although in‭ ‬1917‭ ‬D’Arcy Thompson stated that‭ “‬Even now the zoologist has scarce begun to dream of defining in mathematical language even the simplest organic forms‭” ‬the same can be said today. More recently,‭ ‬mathematical modeling has been applied to general aspects of mollusk skeletogenesis through both ontogeny and phylogeny‭ (‬e.g.,‭ ‬Raup and Stanley,‭ ‬1981‭)‬. Our study is exploring how mathematical modeling of ontogenetic and phylogenetic change in Prunum,‭ ‬in combination with experimental studies,‭ ‬can be used to elucidate the mechanisms involved in the direction and magnitude of evolutionary-developmental change. We used X-radiographic images of Prunum species to delineate quantitative parameters that could in turn be used to model hypothetical and actual skeletal morphologies. These parameters were entered into the software program CerioShell‭ (‬Stone,‭ ‬1995‭)‬. We modeled hypothetical shell morphologies that could be used to interpret the boundaries of possible morphological change in Prunum. These results are being combined with experimental and descriptive studies in order to better understand macroevolutionary events in this clade.

A shell can be thought of as a structure that is a tube that travels over time through‭ ‬360‭ ‬degrees of space.  These revolutions or turns of a coiled shell are called whorls,‭ ‬which are considered to spiral around an imaginary central axis.  This axis runs through the central column of the shell and is known as the columella. The speed at which the whorls enlarge can vary,‭ ‬and a continuous line separates each whorl and is referred to as a suture.  In most shells,‭ ‬the largest whorl of a shell is the last whorl‭ (‬body whorl‭)‬.  ‭ ‬The spire is considered to be all the whorls except the last. The apex is the tip of the spire and the opposite end is referred to as the base. The animal extends out of its shell through an opening called the aperture.

Shells can be viewed in apical,‭ ‬basal,‭ ‬apertural and abapertural views. ‭(‬The‭ "‬usual‭" ‬orientation of a shell is an apertural view,‭ ‬with the aperture toward the viewer and with the apex pointing up.‭)‬

A method for counting whorls is seen below.  First,‭ ‬the shell should be viewed from the apical view and then it should be determined where the first suture begins.  A line can be then drawn dividing the shell into two parts.  Whorls are counted from this line,‭ ‬and are estimated to a quarter of a whorl.

A shell can be viewed as a series of apertures that travel through time and space as the animal accretes‭ (‬i.e. builds‭) ‬its shell.  It is possible to trace the path of the aperture via coordinates of the center of each whorl’s aperture as well as the horizontal and vertical radius of the aperture.

This trajectory can be graphically and mathematically represented.  Once a mathematical formulation is made,‭ ‬it is then possible to vary parameters and modify the mollusk’s skeletogenesis.

The rate of neonatal and infant mortality in Indonesia remained rather static for the last ten years.  While the country is on track to meet many of the Millennium Development Goals, such as the water and sanitation targets, the rates of improvement for child and maternal health are woefully short of the improvements needed to meet their target goals by 2015.  The multiple reasons for these shortcomings will be discussed below, and point to a need to strengthen the health system rather than focus on programmatic interventions.
	Indonesia has made improvements in the number of births with a skilled health worker attending, with 72% of births now meeting this target.  That being said, this category still includes traditional workers, such as midwives, who cannot provide medical interventions should the pregnancy be complicated (hence the large percentage of maternal deaths caused by hemorrhage).  In other words,  the improvements made in this particular indicator are somewhat misleading and there is still much work to be done.  In addition, there has been a decline in the percentage of diarrheal cases in children under five years treated by a health professional.  While data on postnatal care is incomplete, it is clear that this area is also of concern, with low rates across the country.
	Cesarian-section rates are still lower than should be expected, around 4%.  The c-section rates additionally point to another concerning issue.  While the rate of c-section is 7% in urban settings, it is only 2% in rural.  This points to the problem of equity of coverage across the country.  Clearly access to healthcare services is focused around urban areas.  Another issue of access concerns vertical equity.  There is a 27% gap in service utilization between the poorest and richest quintiles.  Clearly the poor are finding it much more difficult to access healthcare services, likely due to out of pocket costs.
	In discussing next steps towards improving neonatal and maternal care indicators, the most basic question is how to most effectively address the lack of service.  Specifically, should Indonesia develop program-specific approaches or strengthen the overall health system without focusing on pre and post-pregnancy care for the mother and child.  There is no question that programmatic approaches to solve the problems outlined above are attractive.  Not only do “vertical approaches” that target one sector of improvements have much more targeted, manageable objectives, they also generally generate faster results.  There are some drawbacks to keep in mind, however.  One major drawback is that investing heavily in programming for one particular area of the health sector often means that funding for other areas suffers and human resources will flock towards working in that area that has more resources (the effect of international funding to HIV/AIDS and its effect on the family planning sector is one example).  In addition, running multiple parallel programs for one area results in duplication of services that are also uncoordinated between programs.  This leads to an increase in forms and paperwork for supplies and funding.

‎	‏The classification of Popular Music has grown over the past‭ ‬100‭ ‬years to include so many genres that it is difficult to definitively list them all. Complicating matters,‭ ‬most if not all genres—rap,‭ ‬rock,‭ ‬country,‭ ‬jazz,‭ ‬folk,‭ ‬just to name a few—have spawned multiple sub and sub-sub genres within their domain.  Arguably the sub-genre of Heavy Metal rock has become one of the most diverse and expressive genres of all popular music in the past‭ ‬40‭ ‬years. It is expressive because it displays a wide range of emotions,‭ ‬although they tend to lean toward the darker side of the spectrum. It is diverse in that quite soon after the beginnings of the genre,‭ ‬people started to realize that it had real flexibility and started to take advantage of it to create their own sub-genre,‭ ‬which then was followed by sub-sub-genres,‭ ‬and the chain continues until today. 

Today we have reached a point in the heavy metal movement where there are so many niches of groups that it is hard to determine what exactly heavy metal is. It has grown to incorporate so many themes from other genres,‭ ‬but like everything else,‭ ‬it spawned from somewhere. In order to properly understand the metal music that exists everywhere today,‭ ‬one must first understand what the metal movement is,‭ ‬and why it’s a movement rather than just a genre.

‎	‏Metal is,‭ ‬in many ways,‭ ‬a movement defined by darkness. Metal can be considered a‭ “‬music of more‭”—‬more bass,‭ ‬more volume,‭ ‬more violence,‭ ‬more theatricality. Less primitivism,‭ ‬more chops‭; ‬people in metal bands really know how to play their instrument,‭ ‬and it comes through in the music. Metal is also—although it may not come as a surprise—a movement that is heavily drug induced. There was a psychedelic drug boom in the mid-70‭’‬s that led to people getting crazier,‭ ‬leading to them to make crazy,‭ ‬other-worldly records,‭ ‬using the drugs as a scapegoat for their creation. It possesses many dark,‭ ‬visceral qualities,‭ ‬which was very new to the music scene because a large amount of popular music had qualities that weren’t true to the darker side of the emotional spectrum. Also,‭ ‬later generations of metal have taken some of their influence from the dark,‭ ‬visceral qualities that were so present in the Romantic Era. Lyrics such as the following express the darkness that is such a staple of the movement:‭ (‬Byrne‭)‬


	
These lyrics from Helter Skelter display the darker side of the Beatles. It exhibits an up and down,‭ ‬supposedly that of drugs. This song is considered by some to be one of the first Heavy Metal songs. It was a response to a Rolling Stones song that was also on the heavier,‭ ‬darker side. The Beatles wanted to prove that they could be just as heavy as the Stones,‭ ‬so they put that song on‭ ‬The White Album.

A few decades before the Surrealist artists began painting their dreamlike works, the artist Henri Rousseau was carefully crafting his own dreams, literally and figuratively. The Dream, a 1910 painting by the famous Post-Impressionist artist, represents not only a woman in awe at the wonders of the land she visits within a dream, but also Rousseau’s own personal dreams and goals as a painter. Since beginning his work, he dreamed of recognition, acceptance, and praise by other artists and art lovers, and found that he was faced with a difficult internal dilemma to achieve this aspiration. The Dream is Henri Rousseau’s work that best reflects his career-long internal struggle: to either conform to or mimic certain styles of painting in order to be accepted by the critical art world he so adored, or to allow himself to be creatively independent and unique, leaving his own path as he went.
Before one can analyze The Dream through this perspective, one must first be somewhat familiar with Rousseau’s biographical story. Henri Rousseau was born on May 21, 1844, in the town of Laval in northwest France. His father was a tinsmith and hardware dealer who “enjoyed bourgeois prosperity” (Shattuck 47). Growing up, he received no formal training in the arts; instead, he was employed until the age of forty working for France as a gabelou, or employee of the municipal toll service, although he received the misnomer sobriquet of douanier, a customs inspector (Shattuck 46). The death of his first wife, Clémence, which followed the deaths of eight infant children, left Rousseau with only one child, a daughter named Julia, and immense grief (Shattuck 49). He therefore hoped to take refuge in a new life and pursued painting to offer him comfort and fresh beginnings. Unlike contemporary colleagues of Rousseau who sentimentalize and romanticize the peasant in painting, he is essentially a folk painter and has the hopes and dreams of the average member of his class.
Rousseau’s obsession with being accepted by the art world is somewhat understandable when evaluated in context: as discussed, he was not only uneducated in the ways of formal painting and began his career at a much older age, but he was producing works at the same time as many other talented and better-known modern artists. Though working for many years already, Rousseau did not begin to receive proper recognition for his art until around the same time that Matisse had begun crafting a reputation as an artist. In the book Modern French Painters, author Jan Gordon asserts that the two, while technically competitors in the art arena, were different not only in style and subject matter but also their reasons for painting in the first place: “Matisse was a painter who conceived a terror of painting in a trite way, while Rousseau’s desire was to paint a picture so conventional that he would be admitted to the Artiste Français” (92).

Many a great thinker has postulated an intimate connection between ethics and aesthetics, between truth and beauty. I believe that at a fundamental level there is a reason for this. As John Keats says in “Ode on a Grecian Urn”, “Beauty is truth, truth beauty- That is all / Ye know on earth, and all ye need to know.” Much of what we know in life is learned via education or experience. However, we seem to appreciate ethics and aesthetics, as Keats implies, without being taught in these expected ways. Both ethics and aesthetics are an attempt to describe rather then prescribe. Our studies of morality and beauty are, for the most part, attempts to explain why a piece of art or literature is beautiful, or why an action is moral, rather than a set of rules for judging, or creating, good art or moral behavior. 
	More to the point, criticism of art or morals is never able to fully capture the essence of what is good or what is beautiful. A conversation about the worth of da Vinci's Mona Lisa, for example, may center around concepts like foreground, background, contrast, or cultural context, but in the end, these do not describe why it is good art. Rather, when one is asked about a favorite work of art or literature it is common to hear a phrase similar to, “There's just something about it” preceding a more complex or critical explanation. I believe that both art and morals can never be completely reduced to a description of their qualities. As Flannery O'Connor says, “A story is a way to say something that can't be said any other way . . . you tell a story because a statement would be inadequate.” No matter how completely we describe the properties of a work of literature, there is something transcendent which is still left. I believe that ethics has this same property. As Wittgenstein says, “It is clear that ethics cannot be expressed. / Ethics is transcendental. / . I suggest that it is this “something”, this je ne sais quoi, which is art and morality's most powerful attribute, and that this transcendental nature of both ethics and aesthetics provides a connection point between them.
	I believe that morality and art are so closely related because we experience both of them most powerfully at a noumenally, to use a Kantian term. They impact us at a level that can be experienced, but not fully explained. This link is even stronger when it comes to the art of literature. As McKean says, “What most distinguishes literature from the other arts, what is, in truth, unique about the art, is its moral quality. It may be that moral standards are inappropriate to other arts, music, for instance, but they seem to be as relevant to literature as they are to life itself. Living necessarily involves values. . . . Literature is important to us precisely because of the values we find there” .

The Germany of today is considered a strong force, a united country with its own blend of culture from within the shadows of the alps in München, all the way to Baltic sea city of Kiel.  The same culture can be felt from Köln on the river Rhine, through the centre of Germany to the Saxon city of Dresden located on the Elbe. With such a unique culture, it shouldn't be surprising that Germany as we now know it comes from several different sources, and tribes. 

Germania is the ancestral land of the Germans. The origins of the name are highly disputed among scholars and historians. Tacitus claimed that the name came from a Germanic Tribe known then as Tungrians, and that they had previously been known as Germans before they crossed the Rhine and battled the Gaulish forces (Tacitus, 98.) Julius Caesar first used the word “Germanus” in his commentary on the Gallic Wars where he put down the Gauls and battled with Germanic tribes which crossed the Rhine often under mischievous premisses. He took this word from The Gauls themselves, and used it to distinguish between those which he had conquered (The Gauls) and those which he had not. While the origin is uncertain, some believe it referred to a neighbor in the Gaulish language. In the first chapter, of his first book on these wars, Julius Caesar notes: “Germans, who dwell beyond the Rhine, with whom they (The Gauls) are continually waging war.....They contend with the Germans in almost daily battles.” (Julius Caesar, 50-40 BC) Others claim the meaning comes from the spear that they used in warfare, known as a ger (O.E.D, 2010), or perhaps from the Old Irish word garim meaning “to shout”, which indicated the Germans were loud, or noisy. (Names of Germany) 

 The early Roman historian Tacitus recorded in his AD 98 writing “De Origine et situ Germanorum”, which told of the origins of the Germans, that “I should regard (The Germans) as aboriginal, and not mixed at all with other races through immigration or intercourse. For, in former times it was not by land but on shipboard that those who sought to emigrate would arrive.......Who would leave Asia, or Africa, for Italy for Germany, with its wild country, its inclement skies, its sullen manners and aspect, unless indeed it were his home?(SIC)” (Tacitus, 98) 

And who would leave Rome for Germania? Certainly not the Romans, not yet at least. They would send out their conquests into the lands of Germania for goods, and lead the occasional land campaign but in the end they mostly returned back home to their sprawling empire. So as the Germanic tribes began appearing in the middle of the first century, they lived on the borders of the Roman Empire and traded their goods taken from the land, and their skills by serving within the ranks of the Roman army, (Ozment, 2005 pg. 17.)

The play Twelfth Night seems to say that although disguise is in fact useful in perpetrating long bouts of deception, in the end a person must reject that newly formed guise, or else risk losing themselves forever in the process. A big problem with ending a deception, however, is that one may find themselves alienated in the process. Therefore, in the end, one must decide between one’s own self preservation, or the preservation of relationships with those around them. For although some will respond neutrally to discovering that they’ve been tricked, still others will not take the deception so lightly, and will be likely be offended by the whole charade.
The topic of deception in gender role reversal is especially problematic, because it brings up many side issues, perhaps the most important one being, why? Why does the subject feel the need to shirk their own identity and take up a disguise in the form of the opposite gender? In Viola’s case, it is obviously a form of self protection.: “I’ll bring you to a captain in this town/ Where lie my maiden weeds, by whose gentle help/ I was preserved to serve this noble count…” (5.1.247-249)
Having newly arrived in a foreign land, Viola feels it necessary to pretend to be a man to protect herself from would be attackers. Viola’s plan works, but it also alienates her from the women around her, cutting her off from an important support system. To make matters worse, she is apparently so convincing at appearing to be a man that Olivia confuses her with Sebastian, and in effect falls in love with her. “Whither, my lord? Cesario, husband, stay.” (5.1.138) On top of that, she also has to deal with suppressed romantic desires between her and Orsino: “Boy, thou hast said to me a thousand times/ Thou never shouldst love woman like to me.” (5.1. 260-261)
Although this may be a somewhat progressive attitude, to the modern reader, Twelfth Night may be seen as an illustration of how deception may help facilitate the unveiling of suppressed emotions, especially in the cases of Olivia and Orsino. Certain passages seem to hint that the aforesaid characters may have unexpressed subconscious desires that the appearance of Viola/Cesario forces them to deal with. For instance, is Olivia attracted to Cesario because Cesario appears to be a man, or does Olivia really secretly harbor feelings for women? One would argue that this is probably not the case, because Shakespeare’s character Olivia seems more likely to be parodying those people of his time period who judge others only upon their looks. 
This is evidenced by the ease with which Olivia switches her romantic ardors from Cesario to Sebastian, and begins to regard Cesario/Viola as family rather than a love interest: “A sister, you are she.” (5.1.315)

German colonial rule has been noted by various observers for its brutality, notably with respect to the genocide of the Ovaherero and Nama in German South West Africa. Of course nothing so broad as an entire colonial empire can be accounted for by such a simple description. The German colonial empire was as varied in policies and ruling style as it was in geography. Educational provision across the colonies was similarly diverse. When the British took over German East Africa (Tanganyika) in 1919, they found a large population of educated and literate Africans. German educational efforts in Kamerun and other colonies were also praised by contemporary authors. 
The situation in South West Africa (present-day Namibia) presented a stark contrast.  Unlike in East Africa, where the government established state schools and played a prominent role in the education of the natives, in South West Africa the task of native education was left almost entirely to missionary societies that received limited government support. The government did however invest significant resources towards the education of Europeans in the colony, establishing s system of state schools as well as more heavily supporting and regulating missionary schools. These educational policies had longstanding effects on South West Africa, even after German rule. While other German colonies boasted significant numbers of literate and educated Africans, in South West Africa “the overwhelming majority of the population remained untouched, uneducated, and illiterate.” Various social, political, and economic factors led to the divergent experience of South West Africa. This paper seeks to expand the discussion by identifying these factors and paying particular attention to new research on the attitudes of settlers and colonial authorities to native Africans.
There is a wealth of literature dealing with education in the German colonial empire specifically. Most of these sources are in German and were written in the early twentieth century, during or shortly after the period of German colonial rule. The aim of early works was primarily to describe the features of educational systems in these colonies. Later writings in English expanded the discourse through comparative studies of education in the various German colonies and more detailed analyses of specific aspects of education. These studies illustrated significant differences in the educational systems of different colonies. The most prominent work to explicitly address the topic of this paper is Cohen’s study of education in South West Africa and East Africa. Cohen compares the educational systems of the two colonies and discusses the factors that account for the differences between them. According to Cohen, the large settler population of South West Africa explains many of the distinguishing aspects of the colony’s educational system.
Compared to Germany’s other colonial possessions, South West Africa had a moderately temperate climate, although much of the territory is covered by arid desert. The European population of South West Africa reflected the relatively hospitable conditions. By 1913 nearly 15,000 whites lived in South West Africa, while only 5,336 lived in the colony with the next largest settler population, East Africa.

The United States of America and Mexico are an example of two nations which at one time were beset by an enduring rivalry which spanned 57 years, from 1836 to 1893. (Diehl and Goerts 2000 p. 145).  The high-water mark of this rivalry was the Mexican-American War of 1846-1848, where the United States attacked and defeated Mexico and secured for itself Texas and the American Southwest as new territory.  Many other clashes happened between the two nations, finally abating just before the First World War.   The rivalry began as Americans and Mexicans clashed on key issues such as religion, culture and tradition and had a major clash of material interests (Schmitt 1974 p. 30-31).   
	This is not unlike many other nations who have an enduring rivalry with a neighbor.  Nations which share a border tend to have clashes of interests which lend to the creation of rival positions between the nations.  The United States and Mexico are not unlike many other enduring rivalries between nations which share a common border.  David M. Pletcher (1977) states that “Only in Mexico and Cuba can one find long-lasting overarching American diplomatic problems” (p. 41).  Indeed, both of these nations are geographically close to the United States and have been rivals to the United States, while other nations in Latin America enjoy and have enjoyed good relations with the United States.   
	Religious issues created a rift between the two nations, a problem which has beset many nations through history.  Sally Frahm (2001) states that ”if in the twentieth century Americans were opposed to fascism and communism, in the eighteenth and nineteenth they were opposed to Catholicism and monarchy”  (p.86).  Not unlike the Cold War’s rivalry between the United States and the Soviet Union was part ideological struggle and part a competition over interests each nation deemed vital. In this case, however, the ideological struggles weren’t based on the political structure but on instead the religious preferences of the United States and Mexico.  This distrust grew from the distrust between the English and Spanish.  Inheriting these feelings of distrust from their former colonial rulers was a major obstacle in the establishment of amiable foreign relations between the United States and Mexico.
	Diehl and Goerts (2000) list 17 disputes between Mexico and the United States in the 57-year rivalry period.   The majority of disputes between the rivalry period described by Diehl and Goerts are territorial issues relating to border raids from Mexican territory into Mexico and other frontier problems.  Border raids by bandits and outlaws from on American border towns were a major problem which remained until both the United States and Mexico exerted military force on their borders (Schmitt 1974 p. 97).  
Schmitt (1974) explains the rivalry between the two nation began to abate as “Mexico became clearly dependent on the United States in a substantial way” (p. 109) and finally ended as American ambitions “changed from territorial expansion to economic intervention into Mexico” (p.110) in the later part of the 19th Century.

Fifteen‭ ‬years ago I became suddenly and unexpectedly disabled by an illness I never knew existed. 

 I was a nurse at the time. I had chosen my profession out of a deeply entrenched need for the safety and security I didn't have as a child. ‭"‬You'll always be able to find work‭; ‬people will always get sick.‭" ‬was the mantra I heard over and over as I reached adolescence and beyond. So--‭ ‬even though my dream was to be a scientist or a journalist-preferably a little of both,‭ ‬I chose nursing. 

Nevertheless,‭ ‬there I was:‭ ‬46‭ ‬years old and single,‭ ‬no money in the bank to speak of and unable to work. To this day I am disabled,‭ ‬and after‭ ‬15‭ ‬years of living on Social Security Disability,‭ ‬I have literally nothing left that I can call‭ "‬mine.‭" ‬I get by,‭ ‬but every day is a struggle and an assault on my security,‭ ‬safety and self-esteem. Nothing in my life is certain anymore,‭ ‬yet,‭ ‬there is one thing that I know to be true. I could not have gotten by for all these years were it not for the help of my family and a few good friends,‭ ‬no matter how strong I was. And believe me,‭ ‬when real disaster strikes,‭ ‬you do not feel very strong at all. 

My point is that there will always be emergencies in life-big and small.  There are no guarantees and no matter how well one prepares,‭ ‬some things are just too big to overcome on your own. 

I agree wholeheartedly that we in the U.S. need to stop putting all of our eggs in big government's‭ "‬basket‭"; ‬Lord knows it is moldy‭ ‬and falling apart,‭ ‬anyway. Yet I would much rather see Americans learning to trust one another again‭–‬learning to help each other and to ask for help,‭ ‬rather‭ ‬than have each of us individually clambering out to the backyard to build fallout shelters. 

The Conservatives in the US talk about the‭ "‬rugged individualism‭" ‬that built this country‭; ‬but in truth,‭ ‬what kept our forefathers going in hard times wasn't rugged individualism,‭ ‬it was compassion,‭ ‬mutual respect and the sharing of resources. The pioneers who crossed the Rockies in wagon trains didn't make it to the coast by going it alone. 


So,‭ ‬by all means,‭ ‬be prepared. I am. I have a disaster kit‭; ‬first‭ ‬aid supplies,‭ ‬water purifying tablets and plastic sheeting and duct tape for the windows in the event of a biological attack. I have several flashlights and all sorts of batteries,‭ ‬lots and lots of candles and waterproof matches and canned goods,‭ ‬too. If‭ ‬you have the land and the resources for a small farm and the ability to can or preserve your own food-do it. It's a great idea,‭ ‬as is a wood stove,‭ ‬as long as you do not live in an apartment. 

But while you are at it,‭ ‬get to know your neighbors.

Sometime in the fifth or sixth century BCE, a prince who would one day be called Buddha was born. Over the course of his life, he renounced the world and became enlightened, and his teachings led to the formation of Buddhism—the most orthodox sect of which is known as Theravada Buddhism. The religion is around twenty five hundred years old; it looks different today than it did when Buddha was alive. This can be seen all over, for instance in the Theravada nation of Sri Lanka, where the annual water-cutting ceremony is observed. Monks and laymen alike participate in this ceremony, and it holds some religious significance, despite Buddha never teaching about any festivity of the sort. These differences run all the way from the superficial traditions to the soteriological core of the religion. The Theravada Buddhist community, both from the monastic perspective and from the lay perspective, has had to change its doctrinal principles over time. This can be attributed to forces both external and internal, both hostile and benign.
	There are a number of qualifying terms this discussion will make frequent use of. There is the concept of internal versus external. Here, an internal force is defined as a force borne of members of the Buddhasasana, regardless of monastic status. An external force is any force from non-Buddhists. A hostile force is any force that damages or intends to damage the Buddhist community—a force borne of a negative perception of Buddhism. A benign force is a force that does not wish to harm or help the Buddhist community—though it may end up doing one or the other as a byproduct. These terms will come up repeatedly throughout this discussion.
	First, it is important to investigate the basics of the religion—the doctrines that lie at the core of Theravada Buddhism. Buddhists seek refuge in the triple gem of the Buddha, the Dhamma, and the Sangha. The Dhamma is essentially comprised of the Tripitaka—the three baskets—of Buddhist text. The Sutta Pitaka contains all the Suttas, the Vinaya Pitaka contains the disciplinary rules, and the Abhidhamma Pitaka contains the metaphysical components of Buddhism. The metaphysical notions consist of things like Anatta—no soul, Dukkha—inherent suffering in life, and Anicca—impermanence of everything. Only by recognizing these concepts can one end Sansara, the cycle of death and rebirth, which happens continuously. Along with Sansara will end lobha—desire, dosa—hatred, and moha—delusion, when one becomes enlightened. In the Vinaya Pitaka, rules for life are set forth. For laymen, there are five precepts (I shall not kill, I shall not lie, I shall not steal, I shall not misbehave sexually, and I shall not take intoxicating substances). For monks, there are many more disciplinary rules to be followed. The most fundamental doctrinal notion in Buddhism is the notion of the four noble truths. First, Dukkha; the truth that life is suffering. Second, that attachment causes suffering. Third, that suffering can be overcome.

In my quest to pursue an education in the social work discipline, my ambition is to follow a career trajectory within the Division of Family and Children Services. The principal objective is to offer assistance to children who have endured abuse or neglect, and to extend support to troubled families. The values I can contribute to the social work field encompass service, respect for others, an ethical demeanor, a commitment to fostering stronger relationships between individuals, and a dedication to continuous professional growth to maintain competence in the field. These core values are not merely crucial to social workers; they are deeply ingrained in my personal being.

Throughout my academic journey in high school and college, I have observed numerous individuals retreating from their problems through denial and embracing coping strategies that were suboptimal. These experiences have steered me towards pursuing a Bachelor’s degree in Psychology, though I was still undecided about my future career path after graduation from Piedmont College in 2009. Taking a sabbatical after college, I visited a friend one summer. She introduced me to a sixteen-year-old boy who seemed anxious on her couch. She explained why he was there — to flee his abusive parents. The next day, I learned he had called the police to his parents' residence. Out of a desire to assist, I drove over to his parents' house. I discussed my concerns with the police, who asked me to speak with the parents since they were powerless to intervene legally. The parents appeared anxious and attributed their son's "manipulative" behavior for reaching out to outsiders to resolve "trivial" disagreements. This encounter sparked a serious consideration of a career in social work to assist children grappling with family disputes.

Moreover, another value integral to social work is social justice. Society often asserts the importance of the individual and mourns those lost. Yet, the concept of the "individual" society holds is often a reflection of outdated traditions rather than unique qualities. If society mourns lost individuals, why do we strive to conform to "everyone else?" I am an individual who rejects self-imposed limitations to fit societal norms. My high school and college years were marked by protests against social injustice: unnatural hair colors, distinctive clothing choices, multiple ear piercings beyond the norm, involvement with GSBA (Gay Straight Bisexual Alliance), and advocating against racism and discrimination. I believe in social justice and will continue to stand against social injustice.

This essay delves into the Biological and Sociocultural perspectives on insomnia. The Biological model centers around genetic traits and health conditions, while the Sociocultural model examines environmental factors and their connection to race, ethnicity, and socioeconomic status. This analysis explores these models, highlighting key research pieces that relate to and elucidate them. Each study's findings are then critically evaluated for their specific strengths and weaknesses.

Insomnia can be categorized into Primary Sleep Disorders, Sleep Disorders linked to other mental conditions, or Sleep Disorders linked to medical issues or substance intake. Primary Sleep Disorders include Dyssomnias and Parasomnias. Dyssomnias, such as Primary Insomnia and Primary Hypersomnia, each present distinct challenges, such as difficulties in initiating or maintaining sleep. Parasomnias, like Nightmare Disorder and Sleepwalking Disorder, involve unusual behaviors or physiological occurrences during sleep. Sleep issues related to mental disorders can stem from Axis I (Clinical Disorders) or Axis II (Personality Disorders or Mental Retardation). This review primarily focuses on insomnia and other primary sleep disorders as they relate to the Biological and Sociocultural models.

The Biological model of sleep disorders emphasizes genetics, inheritance, and physiological aspects. Orexin-producing neurons in the hypothalamus play a crucial role in regulating sleep and wakefulness. A study on mice revealed the presence of phenotypic GABAB receptors on these orexin neurons, which directly influence sleep-wake states. Activation of the GABAergic system promotes sleep, and its inhibition can reduce anxiety and induce sleep. The use of a GABA agonist, baclofen, increased sleep time in the study. This suggests that human sleep patterns may be influenced by similar genetic and environmental factors. A defective or absent receptor could disrupt sleep without medication, potentially impacting daily life and productivity.

This composition delves into three primary facets of Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD). Initially, a concise description of the disorder is offered. Subsequently, the diagnostic process is detailed, encompassing common indicators, also known as "red flags". Finally, the paper concludes with strategies for a teacher in an inclusive classroom to support a student with CAPD.

CAPD, or Auditory Processing Disorder (APD), is characterized by the efficiency and effectiveness of the central nervous system (CNS) in utilizing auditory information. In simpler terms, it is a condition where the brain struggles to process sounds it hears, despite normal hearing. Individuals with CAPD can hear clearly but face challenges in separating words or discerning speech from background noise.

The roots of CAPD can be traced back to the mid-1950s, initially referred to as "auditory imperception" (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005). Italian researchers Bocca, Calearo, and Cassinari pioneered diagnostic tools for children with communication disorders in 1954. Kimura's introduction of dichotic testing and his model for the physiology of the central nervous system underlying dichotic perception in 1961 further advanced the field. A pivotal national conference in 1977 stimulated research into CAPD.

Manifestations of CAPD include difficulties in localizing sounds, distinguishing between sounds, recognizing sound patterns, discerning changes in speech, and synthesizing sound clues. In diagnosing CAPD, a systematic observation of the patient's listening behavior and performance on auditory function tests is crucial. While there is no single diagnostic test with high success rates, and no known cause for the disorder, various methods are employed to evaluate auditory-related skills. These typically involve questionnaires, observations, and tests that present multiple simultaneous auditory stimuli.

In the play "Twelfth Night," it appears that while disguise can serve as a means to perpetuate prolonged deception, ultimately, one must shed this new persona or risk losing oneself indefinitely. One significant hurdle in ending a deceptive ruse, however, is that it may lead to feelings of isolation. Consequently, one must choose between their self-preservation or the preservation of their relationships with others. Though some may react passively to the revelation of deception, others may take offense and be displeased with the entire charade.

The theme of deception in gender role reversal is particularly contentious, as it raises several interconnected issues. At its core is the question: Why does the individual feel compelled to abandon their true identity and adopt a disguise of the opposite gender? In Viola's case, her motivation is clear: self-protection. Having arrived in an unfamiliar land, she resolves to pose as a man for her safety. Her strategy succeeds, but it also isolates her from the female companionship she once had, leaving her unsupported. Moreover, her convincing portrayal of masculinity leads Olivia to mistake her for Sebastian and fall in love with her. "Whither, my lord? Cesario, husband, stay," Olivia exclaims (5.1.138). Additionally, she experiences suppressed romantic feelings towards Orsino: "Boy, thou hast said to me a thousand times/ Thou never shouldst love woman like to me" (5.1.260-261).

While this may reflect a more open-minded attitude, to a contemporary audience, "Twelfth Night" can be seen as an example of how deception can uncover hidden emotions, especially in the cases of Olivia and Orsino. Certain scenes suggest that these characters may harbor unexpressed subconscious desires that Viola/Cesario's appearance forces them to confront. For instance, is Olivia drawn to Cesario because he appears male, or does she secretly harbor feelings for women? It is unlikely that this is the case, as Shakespeare's Olivia seems to parody those of her time who judge others solely on appearances.

This is evident in Olivia's swift shift in romantic affections from Cesario to Sebastian, and her subsequent view of Cesario/Viola as family rather than a love interest: "A sister, you are she," she declares (5.1.315).

The harsh legacy of German colonial governance, particularly in German South West Africa, has been spotlighted by numerous observers due to the infamous Ovaherero and Nama atrocities. However, it would be reductive to attribute the vast German colonial empire's dynamics solely to this singular narrative. The empire's policies and governing styles were as varied as its geographical expanse. Educational initiatives, similarly, varied among colonies. While the British takeover of German East Africa (Tanganyika) in 1919 revealed a populace with considerable educational attainment, German educational endeavors in Kamerun and other colonies also garnered favorable remarks from contemporaries. Conversely, the education landscape in South West Africa (now Namibia) presented a stark contrast. Unlike East Africa, where state schools played a significant role, native education in South West Africa was predominantly managed by missionary societies, with minimal government involvement. The colonial government, though, lavished resources on European education, establishing state schools and supporting missionary institutions. These policies had enduring influences on South West Africa long after German rule. Contrarily, while other German colonies boasted substantial literate and educated populations, South West Africa remained largely untouched, uneducated, and illiterate. A multitude of social, political, and economic factors contributed to this disparity. This paper aims to delve into these factors, with a particular focus on recent research into the views of settlers and colonial authorities towards native Africans. Extensive literature on education in the German colonial empire exists, much of which is in German and hails from the early 20th century, during or shortly after the colonial era. Early works centered on describing educational systems, while later English-language works broadened the discussion with comparative studies and in-depth analyses. These studies revealed significant variations among educational systems in different colonies. Cohen's research on education in South West Africa and East Africa stands out as a seminal work, comparing these colonies' educational systems and explaining the factors behind their differences. Cohen attributes many of South West Africa's distinguishing educational features to its large settler population. Compared to other German colonies, South West Africa possessed a moderately temperate climate, with many areas being arid desert. This climate brought a relatively hospitable environment for European settlers. By 1913, nearly 15,000 Europeans resided in South West Africa, while only 5,336 lived in the colony with the next largest settler population, East Africa.

The categorization of Popular Music has evolved over the past century to encompass a multitude of genres, making it challenging to enumerate them all. Intricately, many genres, including rap, rock, country, jazz, and folk, have given rise to numerous sub-genres and sub-sub-genres. Notably, the Heavy Metal rock genre has emerged as one of the most multifaceted and expressive in the past four decades. Its expressiveness stems from the wide array of emotions it conveys, often leaning towards the darker spectrum. This genre's diversity lies in its early recognition of adaptability, leading to the creation of sub-genres and sub-sub-genres, a process that continues to this day.

Today's Heavy Metal landscape is so fragmented that pinpointing a definitive definition of the genre is difficult. It has assimilated themes from various other genres but, like any movement, it has its roots. To comprehend the Metal music prevalent today, understanding the Metal movement and its distinction from a mere genre is crucial.

Metal, in many ways, is a movement characterized by darkness. It can be deemed a "music of more"—more bass, more volume, more intensity, and more theatricality. Less primitive, more proficient; musicians in Metal bands possess exceptional instrumental skills, evident in their music. Additionally, Metal is a movement that has been heavily influenced by drug culture. The psychedelic drug boom in the mid-70s led to the recording of more intense, otherworldly music, with drugs serving as a catalyst for creativity. It embodies dark, visceral qualities, which were relatively new to the music scene, as many popular genres emphasized lighter emotions. Furthermore, later generations of Metal have drawn inspiration from the dark, visceral qualities prevalent in the Romantic Era.

Lyrics such as the following exemplify the darkness inherent to this movement:

These lyrics from "Helter Skelter" by The Beatles illustrate the darker side of the band's music, mirroring the ups and downs of drug influence. This song is considered by some to be an early Heavy Metal track. It was a response to a heavier, darker Rolling Stones song, with The Beatles aiming to demonstrate their ability to match the Stones' intensity. The song was included on The White Album.

Prior to the emergence of Surrealist artists, a decade or so before their inception, Henri Rousseau was assiduously cultivating his own dreamscapes, both literally and metaphorically. His 1910 masterpiece, "The Dream," is not merely a portrayal of a woman marveling at a dreamland's wonders, but also a reflection of Rousseau's own aspirations and inner conflicts. For years, he yearned for recognition, acceptance, and esteem from fellow artists and art enthusiasts, but found himself grappling with a profound internal dilemma. Should he conform to or imitate established artistic styles to gain acceptance, or forge his own unique path, he pondered. "The Dream" encapsulates Rousseau's lifelong struggle: the desire to be acknowledged versus the urge to remain creatively independent.

To fully appreciate "The Dream" from this perspective, one must first acquaint oneself with Rousseau's life story. Born in Laval, France, in 1844, he hailed from a humble background. His father was a tinsmith and hardware merchant who enjoyed modest success. Growing up, Rousseau lacked formal art education; instead, he worked as a gabelou for France until the age of forty. Known as the "douanier," he was a customs inspector. The loss of his first wife, Clémence, and eight infant children left him with a daughter named Julia and profound sorrow, driving him to painting as a source of solace and new beginnings. Unlike his contemporaries, Rousseau did not sentimentally romanticize the peasant in his art; he was a folk painter with the hopes and dreams of his class.

Rousseau's yearning for art world acceptance is reasonable when considered in context. He lacks formal training and began his artistic journey later in life, working alongside more renowned artists. He didn't receive due recognition until around the same time Matisse was making a name for himself. Author Jan Gordon notes that while both were rivals in the art world, they differed not only in style and subject matter but also in their motivations: "Matisse feared painting tritely, while Rousseau aimed to create a conventional painting to secure admittance to the Artiste Français" (92).

In the realm of intellectual discourse, numerous minds have posited a deep affinity between ethics and aesthetics, between truth and beauty. I hold the conviction that this affinity is grounded in an intrinsic essence. As the words of John Keats in his poem "Ode on a Grecian Urn" aptly convey, "Beauty is truth, truth beauty—that is all / Ye know on earth, and all ye need to know." While much of our knowledge is acquired through formal education or life's experiences, our appreciation for ethics and aesthetics seemingly transcends these conventional paths. Both ethics and aesthetics, it seems, seek to elucidate rather than dictate. Our explorations of morality and beauty are largely efforts to comprehend why a work of art or literature is deemed beautiful, or why an action is deemed moral, rather than rigid rules for assessment or creation. In essence, the criticism of art or morals can never fully encapsulate the essence of what is deemed good or beautiful. Take the Mona Lisa, for instance. A discourse on its value might delve into elements such as foreground, background, contrast, or cultural context, but ultimately, these elements do not encapsulate why it is considered a masterpiece. Often, when asked about a favored piece of art or literature, one hears phrases like, "There's just something about it," preceding a more intricate or analytical explanation. I contend that both art and morality possess an ineffable quality, a je ne sais quoi, that cannot be fully captured in a description of their attributes. Ethics, much like art, possess a transcendental nature. As Wittgenstein puts it, "It is clear that ethics cannot be expressed. Ethics is transcendental." This ineffable essence, this indescribable something, is what imbues art and morality with their power, and it is this transcendental connection between them that I believe unites ethics and aesthetics. The shared experience of morality and art is particularly potent at a noumenal level, using a Kantian term, impacting us at a level that can be felt but not fully explained. The connection is especially profound in literature. As McKean observes, "What most distinguishes literature from the other arts, what is, in truth, unique about it, is its moral quality. It may be that moral standards are inappropriate to other arts, such as music, but they seem as relevant to literature as they are to life itself." Living necessitates the engagement with values, and literature holds importance precisely because of the values we find within it.

Germany, a nation of today, is a robust, unified territory that boasts a distinctive cultural tapestry, woven together from the alpine landscapes of Munich to the Baltic Sea shores of Kiel. This unique heritage can be felt in cities like Cologne along the Rhine, traversing the heart of Germany, and the Saxon city of Dresden situated by the Elbe River. The diversity of Germany's culture is not surprising as it arises from a blend of various sources and tribes.

The ancestral home of the Germans is Germania. The origins of the name are a subject of debate among scholars, with some attributing it to the Germanic tribe known historically as the Tungrians. Tacitus proposed that the Germans were so named due to their residence beyond the Rhine, engaging in frequent skirmishes with Gaulish forces. Alternatively, Julius Caesar, in his commentary on the Gallic Wars, used the term "Germanus" to distinguish between the Gauls under his control and those who remained unconquered. He derived this from the Gauls themselves, who employed it to differentiate their foes. Others suggest the name might come from the Old English word "ger" for their spear or the Old Irish word "garim" meaning "to shout," indicating their formidable nature.

Tacitus, in his work "De Origine et situ Germanorum" from AD 98, recorded that the Germans were considered autochthonous, having migrated by sea rather than land. He pondered why anyone would choose to live in the wild, harsh climate of Germania over more hospitable lands like Italy or Rome. Similarly, the Romans, while they occasionally ventured into Germania for resources and conquests, primarily returned to their empire, leaving the Germanic tribes to thrive on the borders.

Gazing down at the tableau before me, my mind was as vacant as a blank canvas. Indifferently, without a hint of emotion, I scrutinized the scene, my analytical faculties at work, yet they remained detached from any cognitive comprehension. Ideas flitted in and out of my consciousness with such swiftness that it seemed I was merely experiencing an endless stream of external stimuli. The calm efficiency of my perception made me question if I even possessed thoughts of my own. Once, a colleague suggested that I acquire "The New Drawing on the Right Side of the Brain" to enhance my artistic abilities. Ever since I was a child, I had been captivated by the idea of drawing, and this book offered insights into the brain's interpretation of lines and shapes. It introduced a technique of framing any subject of study within a square, transforming complex scenes into simpler, more manageable images. Standing there, overwhelmed by the intricate arrangement of a bowl of fruit on a table, I was unable to mentally impose such a frame. The awestruck wonder that filled me was akin to the initial stirrings of the artist's journey, the genesis of my own artistic odyssey, "Brown's Genesis." My fingers touched the chosen tool of my art, and my muscles tensed and released in rhythm with my hand's motion through space, each stroke a testament to my will. Water swirled serenely, crystal clear and unblemished. Matter detached itself, floating away like embers from a dying flame. My hand, anxious and hurried in its second attempt, struck the toilet handle, but the offending package remained stubbornly in place, a slug-like obstruction. Mop in hand, feet firmly planted, a green tie uncomfortably encircling my neck, I scrutinized the offensive deposit. A few more flushes, a few more moments of quiet introspection, then my hand reached for the toilet paper roll, wrapping itself in layers until it resembled a thick, misshapen mop. Straightening up, bending at the waist, my hand lowered into the bowl, mirroring the actions of a cook preparing a Thanksgiving turkey.

The alarming trend of teenage fatalities on the road is a complex tapestry of contributing factors. The National Institutes of Health highlight that the teen brain's immaturity is a significant factor in this predicament. Inexperience, the cornerstone of teenage driving, exacerbates the issue, leading to a surge in fatal accidents, vehicle rollovers, excessive speeding, and road deviations. Peer influence further amplifies the danger, as teenagers frequently drive with their peers, as any sensible individual would know. The Southern California Injury Prevention Research Center's study corroborates this, revealing a direct correlation between the passengers' age and the frequency of traffic incidents.

California and other states have implemented provisional licenses to mitigate these risks, restricting driving hours and prohibiting other minors as passengers. However, these measures are merely patchwork solutions. The core problem lies in the fact that, collectively, teenagers are statistically unprepared to handle the risks and responsibilities of driving. Psychologist Marvin Zuckerman advocates for delaying driving age beyond 18 to allow the propensity for thrill-seeking to subside. By 2010, a new wave of teenage drivers, the 'Boomers' offspring, will hit the road, potentially escalating the fatality toll.

A feasible legislative approach could see schools continue teaching driver's education to lay the foundation for future drivers, but no one under 18 should be allowed to drive. Provisional permits would still be issued upon certain conditions, including practical training hours. The specific number could mirror current state requirements, such as California's 6 hours of behind-the-wheel training and 50 hours of adult-supervised practice. A national uniform policy could effectively protect teenagers nationwide, as these fatalities transcend state boundaries.

The proposed legislation is far from innovative.

While navigating the Library of Congress's collection of early Edison films, I stumbled upon a trove of fifteen trick films produced between 1895 and 1901. These films largely exploit creative editing to create illusions. My analysis primarily revolved around outlining the poetic elements present in the majority of these trick films and examining the unique characteristics of a few later ones. The trick films of the late 19th century are predominantly set-bound, constrained within a static frontal proscenium, with no camera movement, and employing long and medium shots, adhering to the rigid rule of one shot equaling one film. However, a select few films from the early 20th century dare to diverge from these norms by incorporating multiple shots.

A striking commonality among these trick films is their filming within an interior set, framed by a frontal proscenium. The camera remains steadfast in its position, adhering to a static viewpoint. This style draws upon theatrical and vaudeville traditions. One notable example is Uncle Josh in a Spooky Hotel (1900), where actors move horizontally across the frame, never approaching or receding from the camera.

This static composition often results in long and, less frequently, medium shots, with close-ups being entirely absent. This echoes the theatrical and vaudeville convention, where the audience witnessed the entire performance simultaneously within the stage's borders. Actors typically remain in the middle ground, eschewing close-ups.

Most early trick films follow the rule that one conceptual shot equates to a single film, limiting their length to around a minute or less, depending on the frame rate. This constraint also restricts their dramatic potential, favoring brief vaudeville-style tricks like magic and switching acts over complex narratives. However, a closer examination reveals that a single conceptual shot in the viewer's eyes may actually comprise multiple physical shots, joined to create illusions. Consider The Execution of Mary, Queen of Scots (1895), an early trick film. A careful viewing reveals that the 'head' shot with Mary's severed "head" begins midway through, though the film is perceived as one continuous shot.

John Taylor, hailing from Caroline, emerged as a passionate advocate for Republican principles in his era. While primarily an agriculturalist, his agricultural pursuits, combined with his brief political career, marked him as a man steadfast in his views on individual liberties and governance. His agrarian background deeply influenced his stances on sovereignty, the constitution, and the judicial system.

Taylor believed America's fledgling nationhood presented a unique chance to craft an ideal governance model, unhindered by native traditions. He strongly upheld the natural rights of individuals, asserting that these rights are interconnected; the denial of one compromises the value of all. These rights, he argued, should transcend the grasp of the government. He posited that in a state of nature, the physically strong and cunning benefited, but in civilization, this should not be the norm.

To achieve this utopian society, Taylor envisioned a government acknowledging the inherent good and evil in humanity. He advocated for a dualistic morality, asserting, "As government is administered by man, its virtues and vices must be human" (Ibid., pg. 167). He deemed good principles those that safeguard private property, advance agriculture, and discourage capitalism. A government founded on such principles would operate justly despite its leaders' leadership, who, he believed, would inevitably be driven by avarice and self-interest.

Taylor, like many Republicans of his time, championed strict constitutional interpretation. He advocated for a minimal Federal government, limited to the rights explicitly stated in the Constitution, citing the high cost and potential despotism of an extensive one. However, he cautioned against a simplistic, literal interpretation that could become corrupt without reference to the founders' intent. He considered the Declaration of Independence the true charter of the United States, as it more clearly defined the country as a union of sovereign states rather than a single nation.

Upon revisiting Figure 17, a significant downturn in commuter log submissions occurred during the third month of the project, which was somewhat disconcerting. The onset of winter in New England likely contributed, as fewer people commuted by bicycle or foot. Additionally, December marks the end of the fall semester, a period of intense academic activity, and the holiday season, which could have led students and faculty to overlook the commuter log. The project faced the hurdle of sustaining momentum amidst seasonal breaks and the intrinsic appeal of driving. To address this, we implemented the Carpool Challenge Week in March to rekindle enthusiasm, which indeed spurred an increase in log submissions. Another obstacle was the ingrained preference for driving, necessitating robust incentives. We offered gift certificates to local businesses and even considered more substantial prizes like bicycles or hybrid/electric cars, potentially boosting engagement. Altering prize value over time might have further bolstered participation. Initially, gift cards sufficed, but escalating the prize offerings could have mitigated the project's engagement decline.

An exchange-traded fund (ETF) is a financial instrument that mirrors the performance of an index, a commodity, or a collection of assets, much like an index fund, but offers greater flexibility and trades on an exchange like stocks. ETFs offer the diversification of index funds and the advantages of individual stock ownership, such as short selling, margin buying, and purchasing as few as one share per transaction. However, ETFs are typically associated with lower expense ratios compared to average mutual funds. Nevertheless, they come with trade-offs, including commission fees for every transaction, akin to stock purchases. One of the standout features of ETFs is the wide range of available options.

Despite the explicit benefits, it's prudent for a seasoned investor to scrutinize these advantages, particularly diversification, to ascertain their validity and degree. Here, we will assess the ETF IHF by comparing it to its top ten holdings, which account for 63.58% of all assets. Below are the top ten holdings and their respective percentages.

To gauge how these top ten stocks reflect the entire ETF IHF, we will normalize the current percentage of assets to 100% and calculate the contributions of each stock to a portfolio's Beta and return, assuming the portfolio consists solely of these ten stocks in the proportions dictated by the ETF's holdings. The results are as follows:

It's clear from the chart that a portfolio composed of just the top ten holdings yields a 6.11% higher return than the ETF as a whole, representing a 16% increase. Additionally, the Beta of the top ten holdings is 0.12 points lower than the ETF. These findings suggest that a portfolio of the top ten holdings might offer higher returns with a lower risk. However, it is essential to conduct further analysis to determine if these two portfolios exhibit statistically significant differences.

To evaluate the statistical differences, we will calculate the standard deviation of each of the top ten stocks and normalize these values to 100% to compare their accumulated standard deviation with that of the ETF IHF.

"Dream-land" is one of Edgar Allan Poe's self-claimed superior poems. Here, Poe employs the term "Thulé" in lines 6 and 56, which Mabbott traces back to Virgil. Virgil used this term in reference to an island north of Britain, a vestige of the ancient world's edge. While Virgil indeed used this term, there's a more contemporary influence to consider. Poe, with his keen interest in German literature, likely drew inspiration from Goethe.

This connection is significant as it demonstrates Poe's familiarity with Goethe's works. Karl J. Arndt, in his book "Poe's Politian and Goethe's Mignon," highlights the similarities between their poems, concluding that Poe may have been drawing upon Goethe. The Oxford Companion to English Literature notes that Goethe was renowned for his poetic drama "Faust," published in two parts, the first in 1808 and the second upon his death in 1832. Within the second part lies "The King of Thulé," a poem about a king who, after his wife's death, drinks heavily and eventually takes his own life. The parallels between "The King of Thule" and Poe's "Dream-Land" are striking, with both works depicting a king haunted by loss and grief.

Poe references "ultma Thule" in "The Pit and the Pendulum" and uses "Thulé" as bookends in "Dream-Land." These two poems can be seen as companion pieces. In "Dream-Land," the speaker describes Thule as a dark, lonely landscape, haunted by the specters of deceased friends, and devoid of color. This description resonates with "The King of Thule," where the king, bereft of his wife, is consumed by loneliness and despair. It's as if the speaker of "Dream-Land" has stepped into Goethe's poem. Poe would have known of Goethe's work through Tennyson, whom he admired, or through the numerous reproductions that circulated after the original publication.

In accordance with California law, could a patron injured by falling in a grocery store due to an applesauce spill be awarded punitive damages if the store manager, informed twice of the hazard, did not clean it within a half-hour because he was dining?

Given the circumstances, a judge is unlikely to immediately dismiss Jennifer Palmer's case for punitive damages. For such damages to be justified, evidence must be presented that the defendant's actions were deliberate and exhibited a disregard for potential harm, as well as demonstrating that the conduct was reprehensible. Palmer can argue that Martin should have known the risk involved in not cleaning the spill, as multiple incidents of injury had occurred previously. However, while her argument that Martin's actions were outrageous may not be entirely compelling, it is still reasonable considering the six slip-and-fall incidents in 2009 and his failure to address them.

On October 13, 2009 at 5:00 PM, an employee at D&D Markets, Rich Wayne, notified his manager, Paul Martin, of an applesauce spill. Martin replied that he was on a dinner break and couldn't handle the issue. At 5:15 PM, another employee, Mary J. Haddigan, reported the spill, with Martin responding similarly. At 5:30 PM, Jennifer Palmer slipped and fell, sustaining a severe back injury. Before this incident, five slip-and-fall reports had been filed at D&D Markets in 2009. Palmer is now suing D&D for both compensatory and punitive damages related to her injury, and we are considering filing a partial summary against the punitive damage claim.

In California, punitive damages can be awarded for non-contractual wrongs if the defendant acted with "oppression, fraud or malice." Cal. Civ. Code, § 3294(a) (Lexis 2010). The statute defines malice as conduct intending to cause harm or, in the absence of intent, conduct that is "despicable" and committed with a willful and conscious disregard for others' safety. Id. at § 3294(c)(1). Courts have deemed conduct malicious when it involves a conscious disregard of the probable consequences, demonstrating that the defendant "willfully and deliberately failed to avoid those consequences." Taylor v. Super. Ct. of Los Angeles Co., 598 P. 2d 853, 856 (Cal. 1979).

Four years ago, I enrolled in a course on Islam at CBC. The class centered on a contentious debate: the question of whether Islam is inherently hostile. This query seems as pertinent today as ever. Post-9/11, the U.S. media's stance on Islam and extremism has evolved dramatically, shifting from hostility to an unprecedented level of tolerance. In 2001, a presidential candidate named Barack Obama, with a Muslim lineage, was unthinkable. The Prophet Muhammad's biography captivates me, yet it presents a discrepancy with his character. The historical Muhammad appeared coercive, forcefully converting tribes and imposing Islam. In contrast, his biography portrays him as a misunderstood martyr, humbly attracting converts one by one. I find parallels between Jesus' ministry and Muhammad's 'miracles,' such as multiplying mutton and milk for forty men. This narrative style diminishes Jesus' miracle and life, attributing his qualities to Muhammad. Moreover, many stories in the biography appear to serve as testimonials of voluntary conversions, but often relayed through third-hand accounts, which weakens their credibility. Most disturbingly, the work elevates Muhammad as a paragon of godliness, humility, wisdom, and gentleness, yet historical records contradict this portrayal, raising questions about the true nature of his rise to power.

The tenets espoused by Jesus during his life were quickly eclipsed in the course of Christian thought's evolution post-mortem. Examining this trajectory on a grand scale, there's a discernible drift away from the religion's origins. The modern world, however, exhibits a burgeoning consciousness and an unparalleled progressive spirit. Meanwhile, traditionalists, steadfast in their beliefs, may not be numerous enough to sway the collective tide. Among Christians, historical comprehension is poised to expand significantly in the coming years. This understanding will fuel a yearning to disentangle the doctrines that have been interwoven into Christianity over time from the true spirit of its founder. This process, though gradual, is inevitable: a return to Christianity's original form. A movement will emerge, stripping away layers of doctrine, akin to rewinding time, until only the essence of what Jesus brought to humanity remains. When this trend sweeps through the United States and Europe, influencing multitudes to worship as if living in Jesus' time, the church will remain steadfast as a guiding force. However, the theological pendulum will have swung back, resulting in a reduction of diversity and an increase in uniformity of belief and practice. Regional, denominational, and factional differences will give way to similarities. History is replete with such reversions. For instance, Christians were once persecuted by the Roman Empire, only to see that empire later become Christian. Our country has transitioned from African-American slavery to African-American leadership. The imminent reversion in Christianity will similarly revert history, seeking the source and undoing diversity in the process. This transformation will be hastened by an interpretative shift, viewing Jesus' words as metaphorical rather than literal. Thus, what has transpired since Jesus' lifetime?

Traversing history, we find only Judaism, the foundational theology for Christianity. At Jerusalem's Roman takeover in 63 B.C.E., monotheism, divine revelation, and Hebrew scripture authority were at the core. Jewish society was divided into Sadducees, Pharisees, Essenes, Zealots, and the majority common folk.

I contend that The Jungle posits an inherent selfishness within humanity, where individuals prioritize their own advancement over the welfare of others. This is vividly illustrated by the factory owners and managers who strive to expand their enterprises with no regard for those who suffer in their wake. Their insatiable ambition is portrayed by Upton Sinclair, who depicts the factories as "great chimneys, with the river of smoke streaming away to the end of the world". The owners' apathy towards pollution and the well-being of the community is evident in their disregard for the pollution and waste generated by their operations.
